66-76. Stertinius propounds a di- lemma: he personates the ‘creditor Damasippi,⁷ and imagines two alterna- tive forms under which he may offer his loan to his insolvent borrower. He may say at once ‘ Take it and don't repay it.’ In that case surely Dama- sippus is not mad if he assents. Or he may demand bonds and securities‚ which are as useless as the attempts to bind Proteus. In that case he is at least the madder of the two.
